WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.600
I think most of y'all are very familiar with our last keynote speaker.

00:00:04.600 --> 00:00:09.800
He's one of the trailblazers of the world of data science and open source software.

00:00:09.800 --> 00:00:14.300
As the founder of RStudio and the creator of RStudio IDE,

00:00:14.300 --> 00:00:19.400
he has had a profound impact on data analysis and software development.

00:00:19.400 --> 00:00:23.600
His work extends to the development of R Markdown, Shiny packages,

00:00:23.600 --> 00:00:29.100
and, my favorite, bridging the gap between R, Python, and TensorFlow.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:34.000
So, today he's here to share his insights on the exciting Quarto project

00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.900
that is a Jupyter-based scientific and technical publishing system

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:42.400
that's set to transform how we share knowledge.

00:00:42.400 --> 00:00:46.200
So, without any further ado, with a warm round of applause,

00:00:46.200 --> 00:00:53.000
please welcome our last keynote speaker of PyData NYC 2023, J.J. Allaire.

00:00:53.000 --> 00:01:00.700
Thank you very much. It's really, really exciting to be here.

00:01:00.700 --> 00:01:03.599
And I'm here to tell you today about something new, actually.

00:01:03.599 --> 00:01:06.000
Something to tell you about today, we're announcing today.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:09.900
So, that's kind of always fun to do, too, at a conference.

00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:15.300
And by way of a little bit of introduction, actually, most of this has been taken care of.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:20.900
I'm the founder and CEO of Posit, which you probably have never heard of.

00:01:20.900 --> 00:01:29.400
But you have likely heard of RStudio, which is kind of, we renamed RStudio Posit last summer.

00:01:29.400 --> 00:01:32.699
And the reason we did that is that we wanted to take the things,

00:01:32.699 --> 00:01:36.099
we had a lot of success working in the R ecosystem,

00:01:36.099 --> 00:01:38.599
but we wanted to do a lot of the things we had done in R,

00:01:38.599 --> 00:01:44.800
do them much more broadly, to do work that affected all data scientists and all scientists.

00:01:44.800 --> 00:01:48.900
And so we wanted to become a multi-language data science tools company.

00:01:48.900 --> 00:01:50.699
And we are early in that journey.

00:01:50.699 --> 00:01:54.699
I'm going to share with you today a bunch of the work that we've done in the Jupyter and Python ecosystem,

00:01:54.699 --> 00:01:59.000
but we're going to be doing a lot more of it in the future.

00:01:59.000 --> 00:02:00.300
And I'll talk a little bit about that today.

00:02:00.300 --> 00:02:03.599
I'm going to give you a brief orientation to what Quarto is,

00:02:03.599 --> 00:02:07.099
because you likely haven't seen or heard of Quarto either.

00:02:07.099 --> 00:02:11.800
Then I'm going to spend the larger part of the talk telling you about Quarto dashboards,

00:02:11.800 --> 00:02:20.100
and then just a little bit of a footnote about kind of our nature of Posit as a company,

00:02:20.100 --> 00:02:22.800
and how we're approaching Python.

00:02:22.800 --> 00:02:27.300
So let's start with learning a little bit about what Quarto is.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:31.399
And Quarto is an open source technical publishing system.

00:02:31.399 --> 00:02:36.699
You can think of it as sort of taking Jupyter notebooks, converting them to Markdown,

00:02:36.699 --> 00:02:43.199
and then processing that Markdown into lots and lots and lots of different types of output formats and artifacts.

00:02:43.199 --> 00:02:47.199
Obviously, there are tools that do this, like nbconvert already,

00:02:47.199 --> 00:02:50.600
but Quarto sort of takes that to a whole other level.

00:02:50.600 --> 00:02:54.699
It supports not just the kind of conventional output formats,

00:02:54.699 --> 00:02:59.699
like Word documents and PDFs and web pages and PowerPoint presentations and things like that,

00:02:59.699 --> 00:03:05.300
but also specialized project types that let you build entire websites for books or blogs,

00:03:05.300 --> 00:03:07.800
all from computations in Jupyter.

00:03:07.800 --> 00:03:14.199
So the real big idea behind Quarto is to sort of take the work that you do in Jupyter and in notebooks,

00:03:14.199 --> 00:03:20.199
and then reproducibly transform it into various types of production output.

00:03:20.199 --> 00:03:23.300
So again, Jupyter is where the computations happen.

00:03:23.300 --> 00:03:27.100
Markdown is based on another open source project called Pandoc,

00:03:27.100 --> 00:03:32.600
which is a very, very powerful kind of scientific markdown, academic and scientific markdown,

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:38.100
and supports lots of advanced features like citations and cross-references and things like that.

00:03:38.100 --> 00:03:43.300
And again, turn it into lots of different types of output.

00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:46.300
So just some really simple examples to give you the basic idea.

00:03:46.300 --> 00:03:51.300
The first example I'm going to show you will be nothing novel or noteworthy.

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:54.500
There's a notebook here, and we're going to turn that into a web page.

00:03:54.500 --> 00:03:57.300
There's no options. It's all just default behavior.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:04.000
So I say Quarto, turn this into a web page, and it makes a web page that looks largely like the notebook.

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:11.500
But Quarto has a huge number of options for how things are transformed from notebooks into various output formats.

00:04:11.500 --> 00:04:15.000
And for some formats like HTML and PDF, it has over 100 different options.

00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:17.500
So there's lots of ways to tailor things.

00:04:17.500 --> 00:04:23.000
So as a simple example of that, I'm going to change the theme and the highlight style,

00:04:23.000 --> 00:04:27.000
and I'm going to add an ability for users to make comments using hypothesis.

00:04:27.200 --> 00:04:30.700
So I've added those options at the top of the notebook.

00:04:30.700 --> 00:04:34.700
And then when I render it, you can see the theme and highlighting are indeed different.

00:04:34.700 --> 00:04:37.700
And then over here on the right, you can see this commenting bar.

00:04:37.700 --> 00:04:41.700
So that's just an example. Again, there's lots and lots of things you can do with options.

00:04:41.700 --> 00:04:47.700
Another example of this is we have some options that let you show and hide code.

00:04:47.700 --> 00:04:54.700
So we're saying fold the code, don't show it by default, but provide the user tools to be able to show the code if they want.

00:04:55.399 --> 00:04:57.399
So those are document-level options.

00:04:57.399 --> 00:05:02.399
And then we have cell-level options, which are done with this hashpipe special comment.

00:05:02.399 --> 00:05:05.399
Here we're saying we want to make this a cross-referencable figure.

00:05:05.399 --> 00:05:08.399
So when I render this, you can see it looks a little different.

00:05:08.399 --> 00:05:12.399
Now the code is hidden. You can see the cross-reference here.

00:05:12.399 --> 00:05:15.399
And then there's a code menu in the top right.

00:05:15.399 --> 00:05:19.399
And so then when I click on that, I have a way to toggle the code.

00:05:19.399 --> 00:05:22.399
So this is just by way of example. There's lots of other things you can do.

00:05:23.100 --> 00:05:26.100
I just want to get you the basic mental model of I have a notebook.

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:30.100
I add options to it. I specify different formats.

00:05:30.100 --> 00:05:35.100
I add options to the cells, and that tailors the type of production output that I can get.

00:05:35.100 --> 00:05:38.100
So here's another example of making a PDF.

00:05:38.100 --> 00:05:43.100
In this case, we're going to say we want citations to go in the margin.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:49.100
We're also going to say with PDFs, the ideal reading width does not usually use the full width of the page.

00:05:49.799 --> 00:05:53.799
We're going to have a column that's a little bit narrower, but that means we have space in the margin we can use.

00:05:53.799 --> 00:05:56.799
Putting the citations in the margin is a good thing to do.

00:05:56.799 --> 00:06:01.799
But also I've got two side-by-side figures, and I want those to use up more space.

00:06:01.799 --> 00:06:06.799
So you can see in this PDF, I've got the citation here,

00:06:06.799 --> 00:06:10.799
and I've kind of flowed over the margin with the side-by-side figures.

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:13.799
So again, that's just an example of rendering a PDF.

00:06:13.799 --> 00:06:17.799
And there's similar sorts of options for lots of other formats.

00:06:18.500 --> 00:06:23.500
And then finally, this is kind of the final basic Kordo 101 example,

00:06:23.500 --> 00:06:26.500
is making a slide deck with a notebook.

00:06:26.500 --> 00:06:30.500
Here you can see I've specified a different format, Reveal.js,

00:06:30.500 --> 00:06:35.500
and I've read a couple options, a logo, and a slide numbering treatment.

00:06:35.500 --> 00:06:39.500
This presentation I'm doing now is actually done with Kordo and Reveal.js.

00:06:39.500 --> 00:06:43.500
There's a lot of very fancy things you can do with your presentations.

00:06:44.200 --> 00:06:48.200
Here I'll just show a simple example of a slide that has a couple of side-by-side plots on it.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:51.200
And you can see the logo is here, and the numbering is here.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:55.200
So those are just simple examples to give you the mental model of taking notebooks

00:06:55.200 --> 00:06:58.200
and then using options to customize their output,

00:06:58.200 --> 00:07:02.200
rendering them out to lots of different formats.

00:07:02.200 --> 00:07:08.200
So again, briefly, just to understand all the mechanics, what's the basic workflow.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:12.200
In Kordo, it's a command-line tool, and when you have a notebook,

00:07:12.899 --> 00:07:16.899
you say, render the notebook, and by default it'll just render to whatever format

00:07:16.899 --> 00:07:19.899
that notebook declares as its native format.

00:07:19.899 --> 00:07:24.899
But you can also vary that and say, well, I actually want to render to a different format.

00:07:24.899 --> 00:07:29.899
I'll talk about this in a minute, but we actually have another variety of notebook,

00:07:29.899 --> 00:07:31.899
which is a plain text notebook.

00:07:31.899 --> 00:07:36.899
And some users prefer to work with their notebook in a regular text editor,

00:07:36.899 --> 00:07:40.899
have it be readily difficult in version control.

00:07:41.600 --> 00:07:43.600
So you have a plain text version of notebooks.

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:48.600
It's still using Jupyter, it still sells, it's all the same backend, but it's plain text.

00:07:48.600 --> 00:07:53.600
And so you can equally render the plain text versions of documents here.

00:07:53.600 --> 00:07:57.600
This has a QMD file extension for Kordo Markdown.

00:07:57.600 --> 00:08:00.600
So that's how you render, and then there's a live preview server.

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:04.600
So if you were going to work iteratively on a notebook or a QMD,

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:09.600
and you want to have it update every time you save, you can say Kordo Preview.

00:08:10.299 --> 00:08:14.299
Here's Jupyter, you can see I'm running Kordo Preview down here in a terminal.

00:08:14.299 --> 00:08:19.299
And every time I save a notebook, then the output will update in turn.

00:08:21.299 --> 00:08:26.299
And I just want to briefly show you this plain text notebook idea.

00:08:26.299 --> 00:08:30.299
Again, some people like this because it works with any text editor.

00:08:30.299 --> 00:08:34.299
There's deterministic run order of cells, integrates with version control.

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:41.000
I think there's different use cases for traditional notebooks versus plain text.

00:08:41.000 --> 00:08:43.000
Kordo supports both of them.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:48.000
Just to walk you through this a little bit, this is kind of the Markdown cell at the top

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
that provides all the options.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:54.000
This is literally a code cell, the same thing as a code cell inside a Jupyter notebook.

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.000
You can see there it's got a cell option on it.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:01.000
This is a Markdown cell, and this is another code cell.

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:05.700
Just really the same thing as what we saw in the notebook, but just expressed in plain text.

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:10.700
And then kind of the way rendering works.

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:12.700
It's kind of the way you'd expect.

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:16.700
If you're rendering a Jupyter notebook, we're not going to re-execute the notebook.

00:09:16.700 --> 00:09:21.700
We assume that you have executed all the cells in the way you want, in the order that you want,

00:09:21.700 --> 00:09:23.700
to the specifications you want.

00:09:23.700 --> 00:09:27.700
And then when we render, we're just going to take the Jupyter notebook, turn it into Markdown,

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:30.700
feed it through, and create output.

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:35.400
Whereas if you're using the plain text workflow, we're actually going to turn that QMB into a Jupyter notebook

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:40.400
and actually execute all the cells, and then render the final output.

00:09:40.400 --> 00:09:44.400
You can choose to, if you want, when you're using a regular notebook,

00:09:44.400 --> 00:09:49.400
you can have it re-executed every time, if you want, but by default it does not execute.

00:09:49.400 --> 00:09:54.400
And there's various ways to do caching of outputs, so that if, you know, you can use Jupyter Cache,

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:58.400
so that if you're just working on content and you're not updating your computations,

00:09:59.099 --> 00:10:02.099
that you don't pay for re-running all the cells all the time.

00:10:02.099 --> 00:10:06.099
Okay, so that's the basics of Porto, just how it works, what it is.

00:10:06.099 --> 00:10:10.099
But what I'm really here to talk about today is a new output format

00:10:10.099 --> 00:10:14.099
that we're actually announcing today, called Porto Dashboards.

00:10:14.099 --> 00:10:19.099
And the idea here is to easily create dashboards from Jupyter notebooks.

00:10:19.099 --> 00:10:25.099
And these dashboards could be static, sort of produced one time, produced on a schedule,

00:10:25.799 --> 00:10:28.799
or they could be interactive and have like a back-end server behind them.

00:10:28.799 --> 00:10:30.799
I'll show you both of those variations.

00:10:30.799 --> 00:10:36.799
So, just to give you some examples, these are just some dashboards that we created with Porto.

00:10:36.799 --> 00:10:39.799
Dashboards are generally split into rows and columns.

00:10:39.799 --> 00:10:43.799
You can kind of divide up your rows and columns however you want.

00:10:43.799 --> 00:10:48.799
Here you can see there's pages, so you can have multiple pages in a dashboard.

00:10:48.799 --> 00:10:52.799
These are value boxes, which are things for sort of good, you know, top-level values.

00:10:53.500 --> 00:10:58.500
I'll show you five or six examples just to give you a flavor of the sort of dashboards you might create,

00:10:58.500 --> 00:11:01.500
and then I'll get more into the mechanics of how you actually create them.

00:11:01.500 --> 00:11:03.500
So that's one.

00:11:03.500 --> 00:11:07.500
Here's another one that similarly looks a little different, similarly has multiple pages,

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:13.500
and has also value boxes, and this one has a tab set.

00:11:13.500 --> 00:11:18.500
So the author of this dashboard really wants to focus your attention on this visualization,

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:25.200
and then if you want to drill into more detail, you have a chance to use the tabs to do that.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.200
Here's another dashboard that's similar.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:29.200
It has value boxes and pages.

00:11:29.200 --> 00:11:34.200
This one has a sidebar, which is often used like for inputs in an interactive dashboard,

00:11:34.200 --> 00:11:43.200
or it could be used for sort of explanatory or peripheral data that the user might want to optionally hide.

00:11:43.200 --> 00:11:45.200
Here's another pretty simple dashboard.

00:11:45.200 --> 00:11:47.200
This one doesn't have multiple pages.

00:11:47.900 --> 00:11:51.900
Here's an example of a dashboard you might want to rerun on a scheduled basis.

00:11:51.900 --> 00:11:57.900
So you probably want to update this dashboard like once an hour.

00:11:57.900 --> 00:12:02.900
You know, and I think if you think about sort of deploying things,

00:12:02.900 --> 00:12:07.900
if you have a dashboard like this and you have maybe like hundreds or thousands of people who might be hitting it,

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:11.900
you really don't want to rerun all this Python code every single time someone hits the dashboard.

00:12:12.599 --> 00:12:18.599
What you want to do is say, well, the data's not going to change, but once an hour or whatever, once a day or whatever it is,

00:12:18.599 --> 00:12:24.599
so we'll just rerender it once on a schedule, and then people can just access static HTML.

00:12:26.599 --> 00:12:31.599
Here's an example of a dashboard that's built around a deployed model.

00:12:31.599 --> 00:12:38.599
So it kind of starts off with the model card, and then it has some basic information on model performance,

00:12:38.599 --> 00:12:40.599
drift, misclassified results.

00:12:41.299 --> 00:12:43.299
So this is another use case.

00:12:43.299 --> 00:12:51.299
And this also shows that it's pretty easy to have dashboards that incorporate a lot of narrative and content.

00:12:51.299 --> 00:12:55.299
They're not just strictly just like, oh, look, here's like nine plots with no context.

00:12:55.299 --> 00:13:00.299
It's very easy to bring in markdown and bring in links and rich explanations.

00:13:02.299 --> 00:13:07.299
And then here is an example of an interactive dashboard.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:11.000
This dashboard actually has a Python process running behind it.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:18.000
And when you change these checkboxes or this distribution widget,

00:13:18.000 --> 00:13:23.000
it's going to rerender the plots and update the filtered view of the data.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:24.000
So this is different.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:27.000
The other dashboards I just showed you don't have a Python process behind them.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:29.000
This one does.

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:33.000
And I'll in a little bit get into how exactly that works and how we do that.

00:13:33.700 --> 00:13:39.700
And finally, this is a really simple dashboard, probably a little bit simpler than the other ones.

00:13:39.700 --> 00:13:41.700
This is using Plotly.

00:13:41.700 --> 00:13:46.700
And so one of the things that this illustrates a little bit is that Plotly has a bunch of interactive features here.

00:13:46.700 --> 00:13:48.700
It has this timeline.

00:13:48.700 --> 00:13:54.700
Those interactive features are still available even in a static dashboard because everything is done on the client.

00:13:54.700 --> 00:13:59.700
This dashboard essentially has two pages, indicators and data.

00:13:59.700 --> 00:14:01.700
It has two rows.

00:14:02.400 --> 00:14:04.400
And it splits the second row into two columns.

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:11.400
So I'm showing you this last because I'm going to walk you through exactly how we can take a notebook and turn it into this dashboard.

00:14:11.400 --> 00:14:13.400
So take a look at this.

00:14:13.400 --> 00:14:15.400
Remember what it looks like.

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:17.400
And I'll show you what the authoring looks like.

00:14:17.400 --> 00:14:19.400
So here's our notebook.

00:14:19.400 --> 00:14:25.400
And you can see that it has what's called the front matter here, the options.

00:14:25.400 --> 00:14:28.400
And we've said we want to have a dashboard as our format.

00:14:29.099 --> 00:14:31.099
That could be, on the other hand, DocX or Reveal.js.

00:14:31.099 --> 00:14:33.099
Here's a dashboard.

00:14:33.099 --> 00:14:35.099
And you remember we had an indicators page.

00:14:35.099 --> 00:14:39.099
So in my notebook, I create a level one heading called indicators.

00:14:39.099 --> 00:14:41.099
And that creates a page in the dashboard.

00:14:41.099 --> 00:14:47.099
And then I, you recall, the first row was this big wide visualization.

00:14:47.099 --> 00:14:49.099
So I create a row here.

00:14:49.099 --> 00:14:51.099
And I put my visualization in it.

00:14:51.099 --> 00:14:55.099
And now I need to create my second row that has the other two plots.

00:14:55.799 --> 00:14:57.799
So if I scroll down in the notebook, I have another row.

00:14:57.799 --> 00:14:59.799
And I have my other two plots.

00:14:59.799 --> 00:15:03.799
So that's the notebook that's going to kind of feed this dashboard.

00:15:03.799 --> 00:15:09.799
When I Porto render this or Porto preview this, I get the dashboard that we just saw.

00:15:09.799 --> 00:15:15.799
And you can see that things are organized into rows and columns as specified by those headings.

00:15:15.799 --> 00:15:19.799
If we look down to the next page, remember we had an indicators page and we had a data page.

00:15:19.799 --> 00:15:23.799
If I keep scrolling down in the notebook, you can see I have data.

00:15:24.500 --> 00:15:28.500
I have a markdown cell here that just has a link and a little logo.

00:15:28.500 --> 00:15:31.500
And then I'm using itables package to make a table.

00:15:31.500 --> 00:15:38.500
And then when that is rendered in the dashboard, you can see the data page is provided here.

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:42.500
And you get a version of the table that works well in the dashboard and get the markdown.

00:15:42.500 --> 00:15:44.500
So that is the basic mechanic.

00:15:44.500 --> 00:15:48.500
There's quite a bit of additional things you can do, which I'll show you.

00:15:48.500 --> 00:15:51.500
But that's kind of the basic, the way things work.

00:15:52.200 --> 00:15:55.200
You have notebooks that have cells that have output.

00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:56.200
You have markdown cells.

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:59.200
You have headings that give you the structure.

00:16:01.200 --> 00:16:04.200
So yeah, this is actually, you've kind of seen all of this.

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:06.200
You have a navigation bar and pages.

00:16:06.200 --> 00:16:11.200
You have the things that perform layout, like tab sets, rows, columns, and sidebars.

00:16:11.200 --> 00:16:13.200
And then you have the data.

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:15.200
And those are cards.

00:16:15.200 --> 00:16:21.200
And typically you can think your mental model is like a cell in a Jupyter notebook maps to a card,

00:16:21.900 --> 00:16:22.900
and it presents some data.

00:16:22.900 --> 00:16:24.900
And that data can be of all different types.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:28.900
It can kind of be anything that you can render from a Jupyter notebook.

00:16:28.900 --> 00:16:33.900
As it turns out, plots and tables are really popular, value boxes also, and content.

00:16:33.900 --> 00:16:36.900
But you can have anything, maps, any sort of thing.

00:16:36.900 --> 00:16:42.900
Even just like the results of a summary of data or a statistical model or something like that.

00:16:43.599 --> 00:16:51.599
And so I want to underscore that all of the components that I'm showing you here can be authored and customized

00:16:51.599 --> 00:16:58.599
either within the notebook UI, which in kind of my big demo, initial demo, I showed you using a notebook.

00:16:58.599 --> 00:17:01.599
Or you can also use the plain text QMD workflow.

00:17:01.599 --> 00:17:03.599
I'm going to go through some of these in detail.

00:17:03.599 --> 00:17:10.599
And in this, in sort of enumerating them, I'm going to use the plain text version.

00:17:11.300 --> 00:17:13.300
It's a little easier for me to show you all of the structure.

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:15.300
It kind of fits more compactly.

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:21.300
But just know that everything I'm showing you in plain text can also be done in a notebook equally well.

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:25.300
So navigation bar, it's straightforward.

00:17:25.300 --> 00:17:27.300
You can give it a title and an author.

00:17:27.300 --> 00:17:32.300
You have pages in your dashboard, and those become pages on the navigation bar.

00:17:32.300 --> 00:17:37.300
And then if you want to put some nav buttons to provide social links or even just arbitrary custom links,

00:17:37.300 --> 00:17:39.300
those are easy to add as well.

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:44.000
Sidebars, we'll get into this.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
They're kind of essential in more interactive applications.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And you can have sidebars.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:51.000
So here, these are the headings.

00:17:51.000 --> 00:17:54.000
And this is a Jupyter notebook cell, basically, in plain text.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:58.000
So just whenever you see this in these demos, that's a Jupyter notebook cell.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:01.000
So sidebars you can have inside a page.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:05.000
So in this layout, you have a sidebar with a column next to it.

00:18:05.699 --> 00:18:09.699
And that's just like a sidebar that sits inside a page.

00:18:09.699 --> 00:18:15.699
But you can also have a global sidebar where the sidebar is available across all pages in the dashboard.

00:18:15.699 --> 00:18:22.699
So if you want to do a global sidebar, you put the sidebar attribute on an H1.

00:18:22.699 --> 00:18:25.699
And now that will be global to the whole dashboard.

00:18:25.699 --> 00:18:30.699
And you can see we've got a plot page, a data page, and a global sidebar.

00:18:30.699 --> 00:18:34.699
So as I switch pages, the sidebar will remain in place.

00:18:35.400 --> 00:18:39.400
More useful for interactive dashboards, but also can be useful for static dashboards,

00:18:39.400 --> 00:18:42.400
for stuff you want to let the user clear away optionally.

00:18:42.400 --> 00:18:46.400
So layout, you couldn't see this that well in the notebook version,

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:51.400
but those row headers actually had a height attribute on them.

00:18:51.400 --> 00:18:54.400
So when you define a row or a column, you can give it a height or a width,

00:18:54.400 --> 00:19:01.400
which allows you to, in this case, focus the user's attention on the main chart.

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.400
That's the main thing I want you to be looking at.

00:19:04.099 --> 00:19:07.099
And then say these charts are more tertiary or secondary.

00:19:07.099 --> 00:19:11.099
So here you just use the height attribute to drive that.

00:19:13.099 --> 00:19:19.099
Now going back to the initial set of examples we used, you can see how that's used here.

00:19:19.099 --> 00:19:29.099
This has three rows, and each of which has three items, one, two, and one, just a single item in a row.

00:19:29.099 --> 00:19:33.099
But this is a row-oriented layout for the dashboard.

00:19:33.800 --> 00:19:34.800
So that's the default.

00:19:34.800 --> 00:19:42.800
You can also switch the orientation to columns, and in some cases that's more desirable or useful.

00:19:42.800 --> 00:19:45.800
And then with columns, you can set a width.

00:19:45.800 --> 00:19:49.800
So here's an example of, like, you've got one chart, or whatever this is.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:51.800
It could be just a data table or anything.

00:19:52.800 --> 00:19:56.800
Here, it's taking 60%, and then my other charts are here.

00:19:58.800 --> 00:20:01.800
I don't know if I showed this example before. I don't think I did.

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:07.500
This is a column-oriented dashboard layout, where I've actually put the value boxes here,

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:12.500
and I've got columns, one of which has a tab set inside it.

00:20:12.500 --> 00:20:17.500
So it depends on how you're trying to present it, how dense the information is,

00:20:17.500 --> 00:20:20.500
how much you want to focus on one versus many charts.

00:20:20.500 --> 00:20:27.500
But rows and columns are very flexible, and they can nest arbitrarily inside themselves as tab sets.

00:20:28.199 --> 00:20:31.199
So you can pretty much build any layout that you can imagine.

00:20:33.199 --> 00:20:39.199
And specifically tab sets, you just say, this row, rather than have two side-by-side charts,

00:20:39.199 --> 00:20:42.199
I would like this row to be organized as a tab set.

00:20:42.199 --> 00:20:46.199
And now you can see here, instead of having two separate boxes for chart two and chart three,

00:20:46.199 --> 00:20:48.199
it's just going to make tabs for them.

00:20:49.199 --> 00:20:54.199
And in that case, you're not required to put titles on cells.

00:20:54.900 --> 00:20:58.900
Normally, you can have them be untitled and just show the visualization.

00:20:58.900 --> 00:21:02.900
But in this case, you want to put a title, so the tab set has a title.

00:21:02.900 --> 00:21:05.900
So you do that by adding this title option comment.

00:21:07.900 --> 00:21:09.900
And this is an example. Again, I think we saw this one earlier.

00:21:09.900 --> 00:21:14.900
Here's the use of tab sets inside a dashboard, so that's pretty straightforward.

00:21:16.900 --> 00:21:21.900
So talk a little bit about some of the specific data that you'll put in a dashboard.

00:21:22.599 --> 00:21:28.599
Plotly has a lot of reasons why it's an excellent library for dashboards.

00:21:28.599 --> 00:21:34.599
One reason is that dashboards, you have no idea what the size of the browser is going to be,

00:21:34.599 --> 00:21:36.599
including it could be a mobile browser.

00:21:36.599 --> 00:21:41.599
And you really want the plots to size themselves intelligently to the space that they're painted in.

00:21:41.599 --> 00:21:43.599
Plotly does a very, very good job at that.

00:21:43.599 --> 00:21:47.599
So whatever space it is in, it will automatically be laid out.

00:21:48.300 --> 00:21:51.300
I think Bokeh does a pretty good job at this, too.

00:21:51.300 --> 00:21:55.300
So that's one advantage of Plotly, is that you get this dynamic sizing behavior.

00:21:55.300 --> 00:21:59.300
And the other nice thing, I guess this also applies to Bokeh,

00:21:59.300 --> 00:22:04.300
is that Plotly can give you interactive features, even though you don't have a backend.

00:22:05.300 --> 00:22:09.300
You can also use other Jupyter widgets, any Jupyter widget.

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:12.300
So in this case, I'll show you my PyLeaflet.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:18.000
Here you can see that this is going to look better if I can full bleed to the edges of the card,

00:22:18.000 --> 00:22:22.000
and I have padding around it, so I set the padding option to zero.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:28.000
And you can use regular static, like matplotlib, seaborn graphics.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:31.000
When you do that, you have to pay a little more attention to the size.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Like, okay, this plot's going to be a little wider than tall,

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:38.000
so maybe I want to actually emit it that way.

00:22:38.699 --> 00:22:43.699
They'll get sized automatically, but it's not as fluid as the JavaScript-based plotting library.

00:22:43.699 --> 00:22:44.699
So there's pros and cons.

00:22:44.699 --> 00:22:49.699
One of the negatives of JavaScript-based libraries is they embed all the data in the webpage,

00:22:49.699 --> 00:22:55.699
so if you have a lot of data, you really kind of have no choice but to use a regular static plotting library.

00:22:56.699 --> 00:23:01.699
For tables, you can use the tabulate package to create a markdown table

00:23:02.400 --> 00:23:05.400
from many, many types of Python.

00:23:05.400 --> 00:23:10.400
Data frame, matrix, many data structures are supported by tabulate,

00:23:10.400 --> 00:23:12.400
and that just creates a markdown table.

00:23:12.400 --> 00:23:20.400
You can also use the itables package, which gives you a sortable, filterable view of data.

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:22.400
So both are supported.

00:23:23.400 --> 00:23:25.400
Value boxes we showed a little bit.

00:23:25.400 --> 00:23:30.400
The value box, we basically, right now, we'll actually eventually have a package

00:23:31.099 --> 00:23:33.099
that you can just call functions to make the value boxes for now.

00:23:33.099 --> 00:23:35.099
It's a little bit of a workaround.

00:23:35.099 --> 00:23:39.099
We just print a dict with the value box attributes from the cell,

00:23:39.099 --> 00:23:43.099
and you'll see what it looks like here.

00:23:43.099 --> 00:23:49.099
But I wanted to focus you in on the fact that these values can be dynamic,

00:23:49.099 --> 00:23:56.099
so in this case, depending on the value, the icon would change or the color would change.

00:23:56.800 --> 00:24:01.800
So in this case, we're saying the price is up, so we're going to put an up arrow and green,

00:24:01.800 --> 00:24:05.800
but you can imagine if it was otherwise, you'd use a different color.

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:08.800
So that's a dimension of value boxes that are also dynamic.

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:14.800
And then, I think very importantly, you can include arbitrary text content in dashboards.

00:24:14.800 --> 00:24:18.800
Here, you can see I basically just put a...

00:24:18.800 --> 00:24:22.800
This is the plain text version of just a markdown cell.

00:24:23.500 --> 00:24:27.500
So in a notebook, I would just make a markdown cell, and it would work just this way.

00:24:27.500 --> 00:24:33.500
In plain text, you delineate the content with this carved div,

00:24:33.500 --> 00:24:37.500
and then it just goes in alongside your plot.

00:24:37.500 --> 00:24:42.500
So it's very easy to add narrative and analysis and things like that

00:24:42.500 --> 00:24:46.500
in alongside visualizations and tables.

00:24:47.199 --> 00:24:54.199
And the last piece of dashboard components is all cards have this expand icon by default.

00:24:54.199 --> 00:24:57.199
So some of these visualizations can get kind of small,

00:24:57.199 --> 00:25:01.199
so when the user hovers their mouse over the card, they can expand it.

00:25:01.199 --> 00:25:06.199
In this case, it goes full screen, and they can see a more zoomed-in view of the plot.

00:25:06.199 --> 00:25:09.199
You can turn that off if you want, but it's on by default.

00:25:09.199 --> 00:25:16.199
Okay, so that's kind of like whirlwind grand tour of all the different ways you can...

00:25:16.900 --> 00:25:21.900
Components of dashboards, how you present data, how it kind of maps to markdown headers and notebook cells.

00:25:21.900 --> 00:25:25.900
But I want to talk a little bit about different ways to deploy dashboards.

00:25:25.900 --> 00:25:30.900
Most of what I've shown you right now so far are just static HTML pages.

00:25:30.900 --> 00:25:33.900
So they actually can be deployed to any web server or web host.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:38.900
They don't require a Python processor or server, so they're very lightweight, very scalable.

00:25:38.900 --> 00:25:40.900
So that's the basic kind of...

00:25:40.900 --> 00:25:44.900
Static dashboard, if you can imagine, like, the underlying data won't ever change.

00:25:45.599 --> 00:25:50.599
If I have a dashboard about, like, the 2016 election, the data's not going to change.

00:25:50.599 --> 00:25:52.599
I don't need to keep re-rendering it.

00:25:52.599 --> 00:25:54.599
It's just the election, or whatever.

00:25:54.599 --> 00:25:57.599
Or, you know, the Q1, whatever.

00:25:57.599 --> 00:26:00.599
There's some things that's historical data that's not going to change.

00:26:00.599 --> 00:26:03.599
A single static rendering of it can be fine.

00:26:03.599 --> 00:26:07.599
But then, obviously, you want to, in some cases, have scheduled dashboards.

00:26:07.599 --> 00:26:12.599
So, you know, use a cron job or any other kind of job manager to basically say,

00:26:13.300 --> 00:26:17.300
I want to re-render my dashboard every day or every hour or whatever's appropriate.

00:26:17.300 --> 00:26:21.300
You can also have parameterized dashboards.

00:26:21.300 --> 00:26:24.300
And I'll show an example of that in just a minute.

00:26:24.300 --> 00:26:29.300
So you can say, well, you know, the dashboard will...

00:26:29.300 --> 00:26:32.300
Depending on the parameters, it might target a certain region,

00:26:32.300 --> 00:26:34.300
or it might target a certain assumption.

00:26:34.300 --> 00:26:37.300
And in that case, I want to have a different version of the dashboard.

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:39.300
So you can declare parameters in dashboards,

00:26:39.300 --> 00:26:42.300
and then have those create variants of the dashboard.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:46.000
And that works well with both static and scheduled dashboards.

00:26:46.000 --> 00:26:51.000
And then finally, you can have an interactive dashboard that has a server backend

00:26:51.000 --> 00:26:56.000
that uses Shiny, which is another open source project from Puzzit.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:26:59.000
And I'll describe how to do that.

00:26:59.000 --> 00:27:02.000
But when you do that, it requires a server for deployment.

00:27:02.000 --> 00:27:07.000
So I want to speak briefly about the idea of a parameterized dashboard.

00:27:07.699 --> 00:27:12.699
We use the same kind of technique that Paper Mill uses to declare parameters.

00:27:12.699 --> 00:27:17.699
So in Paper Mill, you basically add a tag to a cell called parameters.

00:27:17.699 --> 00:27:20.699
And then you declare a bunch of variables in there.

00:27:20.699 --> 00:27:24.699
And then once you've done that, when you render,

00:27:24.699 --> 00:27:27.699
you can give it this parameter.

00:27:27.699 --> 00:27:29.699
You can have it as many as you want.

00:27:29.699 --> 00:27:32.699
And it'll vary the dashboard based on the parameters.

00:27:32.699 --> 00:27:35.699
So in this case, this is a dashboard for a single stock,

00:27:36.400 --> 00:27:38.400
but you might want to render it for different stocks,

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:40.400
and that parameter allows you to do it.

00:27:40.400 --> 00:27:43.400
So that's parameterized dashboards.

00:27:43.400 --> 00:27:46.400
Interactive dashboards are a whole different thing,

00:27:46.400 --> 00:27:49.400
but they're a really pretty natural extension of all the stuff I've shown you

00:27:49.400 --> 00:27:51.400
with static dashboards.

00:27:51.400 --> 00:27:54.400
Again, these build on Shiny package,

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:57.400
which is another Python open source project by both Python

00:27:57.400 --> 00:27:59.400
and our open source project from Puzzit.

00:27:59.400 --> 00:28:01.400
Shiny is kind of its own thing.

00:28:01.400 --> 00:28:04.400
It's got its own whole application framework and way of doing things.

00:28:05.099 --> 00:28:08.099
In this case, we're just going to embed Shiny components

00:28:08.099 --> 00:28:11.099
inside a Cordo dashboard.

00:28:19.099 --> 00:28:22.099
This is a super simple Shiny dashboard.

00:28:22.099 --> 00:28:24.099
Hello, Shiny.

00:28:24.099 --> 00:28:26.099
You can see on the right, it's just a single plot,

00:28:26.099 --> 00:28:28.099
and it's got three inputs.

00:28:28.099 --> 00:28:30.099
I'll walk you through what the code looks like for this.

00:28:30.099 --> 00:28:33.099
You can see we're still using markdown headings,

00:28:33.800 --> 00:28:35.800
the kind of dashboard syntax that we talked about,

00:28:35.800 --> 00:28:38.800
but we've added this server Shiny to indicate that this dashboard

00:28:38.800 --> 00:28:40.800
should have a backend.

00:28:40.800 --> 00:28:43.800
First, I'm going to call a bunch of functions

00:28:43.800 --> 00:28:46.800
from the Shiny package to define three inputs,

00:28:46.800 --> 00:28:49.800
and those map here to variable distribution

00:28:49.800 --> 00:28:52.800
and whether to show run marks.

00:28:52.800 --> 00:28:54.800
And those are just functions that say,

00:28:54.800 --> 00:28:56.800
here's the variable, I'm declaring it,

00:28:56.800 --> 00:28:58.800
here's the label I want to have for it,

00:28:58.800 --> 00:29:00.800
and here's the choices to offer.

00:29:01.500 --> 00:29:03.500
I'll put those in the sidebar.

00:29:03.500 --> 00:29:06.500
And then over here, we define a function that creates a plot.

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:08.500
This uses a Python decorator.

00:29:08.500 --> 00:29:11.500
You'll see in Shiny there's a bunch of decorators,

00:29:11.500 --> 00:29:14.500
render decorators, and what's noteworthy about here

00:29:14.500 --> 00:29:17.500
is you'll see that nowhere in this file

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:19.500
do we actually call this function.

00:29:19.500 --> 00:29:22.500
Using the decorator basically instructs Shiny,

00:29:22.500 --> 00:29:25.500
please call this function whenever any of the inputs

00:29:25.500 --> 00:29:28.500
that are referenced by it change.

00:29:29.199 --> 00:29:31.199
Shiny will automatically call this function when it needs to.

00:29:31.199 --> 00:29:33.199
And you can see in this line here,

00:29:33.199 --> 00:29:36.199
we're actually referencing those inputs defined above.

00:29:36.199 --> 00:29:39.199
So whenever you see these render decorators,

00:29:39.199 --> 00:29:41.199
you're just saying, set this up to be called

00:29:41.199 --> 00:29:44.199
whenever things that it depends on change.

00:29:44.199 --> 00:29:47.199
So that's a super simple little Shiny.

00:29:47.199 --> 00:29:52.199
You can do quite a bit more sophisticated Shiny dashboards.

00:29:52.199 --> 00:29:55.199
This one steps up a little bit.

00:29:55.199 --> 00:29:57.199
It's still pretty simple.

00:29:57.900 --> 00:29:59.900
It's got a couple pages.

00:29:59.900 --> 00:30:01.900
It's got more inputs.

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:04.900
But all the stuff I showed you with value boxes and tab sets

00:30:04.900 --> 00:30:06.900
and rows and columns and tables,

00:30:06.900 --> 00:30:09.900
you can all do that interactively with Shiny components as well.

00:30:09.900 --> 00:30:12.900
In terms of deploying these things,

00:30:12.900 --> 00:30:15.900
there are quite a few different ways to do that.

00:30:15.900 --> 00:30:19.900
And they're basically standard ASCGI Python apps.

00:30:19.900 --> 00:30:22.900
So you don't need anything special, per se, to deploy them.

00:30:22.900 --> 00:30:25.900
You can just call Shiny run.

00:30:26.599 --> 00:30:29.599
As long as your server environment supports WebSockets and StickySessions,

00:30:29.599 --> 00:30:31.599
then you can serve it.

00:30:31.599 --> 00:30:34.599
That said, there are some easier ways to deploy

00:30:34.599 --> 00:30:39.599
that take care of some of the networking and scaling and things like that.

00:30:39.599 --> 00:30:43.599
So there's a couple cloud services that support Shiny deployment.

00:30:43.599 --> 00:30:46.599
ShinyAppsIO, that's one that Posit has created,

00:30:46.599 --> 00:30:49.599
and then HuggingFace also supports Shiny apps.

00:30:49.599 --> 00:30:51.599
And then if you're running your own server,

00:30:51.599 --> 00:30:54.599
we have an open source server that lets you deploy Shiny apps.

00:30:55.300 --> 00:30:58.300
We also have a commercial product that lets you deploy Shiny apps.

00:30:58.300 --> 00:31:01.300
And then, of course, as I said, you can completely roll your own.

00:31:01.300 --> 00:31:03.300
You don't need to use any of these products.

00:31:03.300 --> 00:31:06.300
They just kind of make some things easier.

00:31:06.300 --> 00:31:10.300
So I did earlier say that whenever you use Shiny components,

00:31:10.300 --> 00:31:13.300
you're going to need a server.

00:31:13.300 --> 00:31:16.300
That's not entirely true.

00:31:16.300 --> 00:31:19.300
We actually have a way to deploy these dashboards that use Shiny

00:31:19.300 --> 00:31:22.300
completely serverless using Kydive.

00:31:23.000 --> 00:31:25.000
So we actually have an example up on our site to show you.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:29.000
You can use Python, use Matplotlib and Pandas and everything,

00:31:29.000 --> 00:31:32.000
and actually have it all run inside the web browser.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:35.000
And then there's no server in that case.

00:31:35.000 --> 00:31:38.000
And so this retirement simulation example we have

00:31:38.000 --> 00:31:41.000
shows you how to do that, and this is the app.

00:31:41.000 --> 00:31:43.000
It's just pretty simple.

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:46.000
It's just got two scenarios, and you can change them,

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.000
and it reruns the simulation.

00:31:48.000 --> 00:31:51.000
But this is all running inside the browser.

00:31:51.699 --> 00:31:55.699
So there is a serverless option that you have.

00:31:57.699 --> 00:32:00.699
All right, so that is now kind of completed,

00:32:00.699 --> 00:32:02.699
telling you all about dashboards.

00:32:02.699 --> 00:32:05.699
I wanted to conclude by giving you a little bit of insight

00:32:05.699 --> 00:32:08.699
into Posit, the company, what our philosophy is,

00:32:08.699 --> 00:32:12.699
and kind of the work we've done so far in the Python space.

00:32:12.699 --> 00:32:17.699
So we were founded 14 years ago as RStudio,

00:32:18.400 --> 00:32:22.400
and our mission was then, and now, and will be,

00:32:22.400 --> 00:32:25.400
to create open source software for data science.

00:32:25.400 --> 00:32:28.400
We're actually organized as a public benefit corporation,

00:32:28.400 --> 00:32:30.400
which means a bunch of things,

00:32:30.400 --> 00:32:33.400
but mostly it means that our mission is encoded

00:32:33.400 --> 00:32:35.400
into our corporate charter.

00:32:35.400 --> 00:32:38.400
Our officers and directors actually have a fiduciary duty

00:32:38.400 --> 00:32:41.400
to pursue this mission, and that when we make decisions,

00:32:41.400 --> 00:32:44.400
that traditional corporations, like a normal C corporation,

00:32:44.599 --> 00:32:47.599
really needs to narrowly consider the interests

00:32:47.599 --> 00:32:50.599
of the shareholders as kind of the only thing

00:32:50.599 --> 00:32:52.599
that really ultimately matters,

00:32:52.599 --> 00:32:55.099
and public benefit corporations can be much more diverse.

00:32:55.099 --> 00:32:58.099
They have their mission, they have the community,

00:32:58.099 --> 00:33:00.099
they have their employees, they have the shareholders,

00:33:00.099 --> 00:33:02.099
they sort of look at all the stakeholders.

00:33:02.099 --> 00:33:05.099
So that's our approach, kind of at a corporate level,

00:33:05.099 --> 00:33:08.099
and we've actually gone to pretty significant lengths

00:33:08.099 --> 00:33:10.099
to try to make sure that never changes.

00:33:10.099 --> 00:33:13.099
So we are an independent company,

00:33:13.800 --> 00:33:15.800
and we are committed to not ever selling the company

00:33:15.800 --> 00:33:17.800
and not going public, so we are always going to be

00:33:17.800 --> 00:33:19.800
an independent and private company.

00:33:19.800 --> 00:33:22.800
To that end, we have control of the company entirely inside,

00:33:22.800 --> 00:33:25.800
so outside investors do not have a way

00:33:25.800 --> 00:33:27.800
to force us to do anything.

00:33:27.800 --> 00:33:30.800
All of the main control is within people inside the company.

00:33:30.800 --> 00:33:33.800
I think that allows us to have an imperative

00:33:33.800 --> 00:33:36.800
that isn't growth at all costs,

00:33:36.800 --> 00:33:39.800
which is, I think, the imperative of most startup companies,

00:33:39.800 --> 00:33:41.800
even most big public companies,

00:33:42.500 --> 00:33:44.500
but try to build something that's sustainable

00:33:44.500 --> 00:33:46.500
and building open source software

00:33:46.500 --> 00:33:48.500
and providing a trustworthy foundation

00:33:48.500 --> 00:33:51.500
for users of open source software for a long, long time.

00:33:51.500 --> 00:33:53.500
A hundred years might be a little extreme,

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:57.500
but as long as possible, a hundred years aspirationally.

00:33:59.500 --> 00:34:01.500
And as I said, we want to be durable,

00:34:01.500 --> 00:34:03.500
we want to be trustworthy,

00:34:03.500 --> 00:34:06.500
we want you to understand that our core motivation

00:34:06.500 --> 00:34:08.500
is to create open source software

00:34:08.500 --> 00:34:11.500
and make it incredible and easy to use

00:34:12.199 --> 00:34:16.199
and let people use code to do data science

00:34:16.199 --> 00:34:18.199
and make it all open,

00:34:18.199 --> 00:34:20.199
and that's kind of our bottom line.

00:34:22.199 --> 00:34:24.199
So we've begun recently,

00:34:24.199 --> 00:34:26.199
actually probably starting about three years ago,

00:34:26.199 --> 00:34:30.199
to work on a lot more Python open source projects.

00:34:30.199 --> 00:34:32.199
So Quarto we heard all about today.

00:34:32.199 --> 00:34:35.199
There's a separate project called QuartoDoc

00:34:35.199 --> 00:34:38.199
that helps with creating package documentation

00:34:38.199 --> 00:34:40.199
for Python packages.

00:34:40.899 --> 00:34:42.899
A bunch of packages are using it now.

00:34:42.899 --> 00:34:44.899
Ibis just switched over to using QuartoDoc.

00:34:46.899 --> 00:34:48.899
We've also got Shiny, which you heard about today.

00:34:48.899 --> 00:34:50.899
So Shiny works inside Quarto,

00:34:50.899 --> 00:34:52.899
but also kind of works Quarto standalone.

00:34:52.899 --> 00:34:54.899
And we have some other packages

00:34:54.899 --> 00:34:56.899
you may not have heard of.

00:34:56.899 --> 00:34:58.899
Betamer for kind of model ops,

00:34:58.899 --> 00:35:00.899
Suba is a data manipulation library,

00:35:00.899 --> 00:35:03.899
and Plot9 is a data viz library.

00:35:03.899 --> 00:35:05.899
So we've got lots of projects,

00:35:05.899 --> 00:35:08.899
we've got a lot of investment in these projects,

00:35:09.600 --> 00:35:11.600
and we'll have more projects over time.

00:35:11.600 --> 00:35:13.600
We're also very much involved with NumFocus,

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:17.600
and we're working closely with the Jupyter community

00:35:17.600 --> 00:35:20.600
on some standards for scientific notebook publishing

00:35:20.600 --> 00:35:22.600
in an effort called NotebooksNow.

00:35:22.600 --> 00:35:24.600
So we're doing a lot with Python,

00:35:24.600 --> 00:35:26.600
we're going to do a lot more in the future,

00:35:26.600 --> 00:35:29.600
and we invite all of you to help us figure out

00:35:29.600 --> 00:35:31.600
what the right tools are,

00:35:31.600 --> 00:35:33.600
what the right path is,

00:35:33.600 --> 00:35:35.600
what things should work well together,

00:35:35.600 --> 00:35:38.600
and I'm really excited to get going on this.

