00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:51.000
So the question is,

00:36:51.699 --> 00:36:53.699
there's another project that's similar to Quarto

00:36:53.699 --> 00:36:55.699
called MistJS,

00:36:55.699 --> 00:36:57.699
and we are working with them

00:36:57.699 --> 00:36:59.699
on the notebooks now.

00:36:59.699 --> 00:37:01.699
One of the ideas was that

00:37:01.699 --> 00:37:03.699
we recognize that there's not going to just be

00:37:03.699 --> 00:37:05.699
one markdown system for Jupyter for all time,

00:37:05.699 --> 00:37:07.699
so we didn't want to make

00:37:07.699 --> 00:37:09.699
the standard for scientific publications

00:37:09.699 --> 00:37:11.699
as one open source project.

00:37:11.699 --> 00:37:13.699
So we worked with them to create

00:37:13.699 --> 00:37:15.699
an intermediate format

00:37:15.699 --> 00:37:17.699
that basically multiple projects can target,

00:37:17.699 --> 00:37:19.699
and so by the time you get to that format,

00:37:20.399 --> 00:37:22.399
there are no vestiges of Quarto or Mist.

00:37:22.399 --> 00:37:24.399
So that was an effort to just make sure

00:37:24.399 --> 00:37:26.399
that the standard was beyond any given project.

00:37:26.399 --> 00:37:28.399
And Mist is a similar project.

00:37:28.399 --> 00:37:30.399
I'd say they're a little more focused

00:37:30.399 --> 00:37:32.399
on scientific manuscripts

00:37:32.399 --> 00:37:34.399
and websites.

00:37:34.399 --> 00:37:36.399
They're not quite as broad

00:37:36.399 --> 00:37:38.399
in the different things they're going after.

00:37:38.399 --> 00:37:40.399
They do have a little different syntax.

00:37:40.399 --> 00:37:42.399
We're actually working with them to try to,

00:37:42.399 --> 00:37:44.399
like, can we get the citation syntax to be the same?

00:37:44.399 --> 00:37:46.399
Can we get the div syntax to be the same?

00:37:46.399 --> 00:37:48.399
But they do have different lineages,

00:37:49.100 --> 00:37:51.100
and so they're not identical.

